\section{Yee Algorithm}\index{FDTD!Yee algorithm}
%After Kane Yee first introduce the FDTD technique in 1966, people began to realize its accuracy and flexibility for solving electromagnetic problems \cite{lee_Algorithm} and keep using it up to the present.

The basic idea of Yee\rq s algorithm is to discretize both the physical region and the time interval of the differential-form three-dimensional Maxwell\rq s equations (in \ref{Maxwells_equations}) on uniformed grids. Then the space and time models are established so the algorithm can update electromagnetic field values step by step from two parts: field values calculated in previous time steps and field values in the adjacent space cells. This model made possible the utilization of modern computation resources on Maxwell\rq s equations, and created a new area of electromagnetic scientific research.

The 3D grid shown in Fig.~\ref{Fig:3d_yee_cell}, named the \lq\lq Yee-Cell\rq\rq, is very helpful for understanding the discretized electromagnetic space. As illustrated in Fig.~\ref{Fig:3d_yee_cell}, the \lq\lq Yee-Cell\rq\rq is a small cube, can be treated as one single cell picked up from discretized model space. $\bigtriangleup x,~\bigtriangleup y~\&~\bigtriangleup z$ are the three dimensions of this cube. We use (i, j, k) to denote the point whose real coordinate is ($i\bigtriangleup x,j\bigtriangleup y,k\bigtriangleup z$) in the model space. Instead of placing $\overrightarrow{E}$  and $\overrightarrow{H}$ components in the center of each cell, they are interlaced here so that every $\overrightarrow{E}$ component is surrounded by four circulating $\overrightarrow{H}$ components, and every $\overrightarrow{H}$ components is surrounded by four circulating $\overrightarrow{E}$ components.
