%A complete FDTD model can be structured as shown in Fig.~\ref{Fig:structure_diagram_FDTD}. 
The model space is first divided into appropriately sized unit cells, each having electrical permittivity $\epsilon$ and magnetic permeability $\mu$ and other necessary parameters. Then all the electromagnetic field components are initialized and the parameters affiliated to each cell will be set up. Excitation will be given later so there will be a power source in the model space. The algorithm then iterates the updating computations for each time step. Notice the $\overrightarrow E$ and $\overrightarrow H$ are interlaced in the time domain so the $\overrightarrow E$ components will be updated first and then the $\overrightarrow H$ components. The boundary condition part is a special algorithm deals with the unit cells located on the boundary of the model space. For these cells, some of the adjacent cells may not exist, so special methods are needed to update them appropriately. Finally, the algorithm gives the result of the electromagnetic space characteristics for the time ranges we are interested in.

